{"title":"Total Stored Water (All Reservoirs) vs Total Usable Volume","analysis_comments":"Across 2015–2019, total stored water varies roughly from ~0.85–1.35 million ML, while the summed usable capacity line sits near ~1.9 million ML. This indicates the system operates well below combined usable capacity for most of the period, with a notable drawdown through 2018–2019 before partial recovery late-2019.

Thomson dominates system storage (largest area contribution), so changes in Thomson largely drive the total stored trajectory; Upper Yarra and Cardinia form the next tier, while O’Shannassy/Maroondah and the smaller service storages contribute comparatively minor variability. The widening gap between storage and total usable volume during 2018–2019 suggests increasing supply pressure and/or reduced inflows over that period, consistent with drought-like conditions.

Data source for plotted series: total_stored_vs_usable_volume.csv.","chart_filename":"total_stored_vs_usable_volume.png","chart_html_filename":"total_stored_vs_usable_volume.html","code_filename":"total_stored_vs_usable_volume.py","data_filename":"total_stored_vs_usable_volume.csv"}

{"title":"2017 Rainfall (Catchment) and Inflow (Streamflow) Time Series – Multi-Reservoir","analysis_comments":"All four catchments show a pronounced wet-season response in late winter–spring 2017: rainfall events from ~Aug–Oct coincide with sustained elevated inflows. Peak inflow magnitudes differ strongly by reservoir: Thomson shows the largest peaks (approaching ~3,000 ML/d), Upper Yarra next (~2,500 ML/d), O’Shannassy (~1,600 ML/d) and Maroondah (~1,000 ML/d), reflecting catchment size and runoff efficiency.

In each pane, inflow peaks generally lag rainfall bursts by ~1–3 days and remain elevated for weeks during the wet period, indicating catchment wetting and baseflow contributions beyond “event-only” runoff. The sharp inflow spikes around September and again in late November/December suggest short, intense rainfall events superimposed on differing antecedent moisture conditions.

Data source for plotted series: rainfall_inflow_2017_faceted.csv.","chart_filename":"rainfall_inflow_2017_faceted.png","chart_html_filename":"rainfall_inflow_2017_faceted.html","code_filename":"rainfall_inflow_2017_faceted.py","data_filename":"rainfall_inflow_2017_faceted.csv"}

{"title":"API Lag Analysis Key Results (Optimal k)","analysis_comments":"All dams achieve their maximum |ρ| at lag 0, so API is most informative for same-day inflow; however, forecast skill varies markedly by catchment.

O’Shannassy maintains ρ≥0.75 through the full tested 14-day horizon (ρ14≈0.763), indicating very persistent inflow dynamics once catchment wetness is known. Upper Yarra maintains ρ≥0.75 out to ~10 days (ρ10≈0.754). Thomson only meets ρ≥0.75 out to 1 day (ρ1≈0.751), and Maroondah never reaches 0.75 (ρ0≈0.717), implying a larger share of short-lived/event-driven variability or additional controls (e.g., localised storms not captured by catchment-average rainfall, operational effects).

Data source: api_lag_analysis_summary.csv.","code_filename":"api_lag_analysis_summary.py","data_filename":"api_lag_analysis_summary.csv"}
